That aside it does have a stellar cast and looks like it may dedicate some time to strengthening Amy's character- who so often gets dismissed as just the pickled limes girl. text: I watch all period films and then score them on how many (nihilist) modernist anachronisms are being forced on me. The British, mainly, have been producing low-anachronism period films and series now for a few years -- and some of them are simply wonderful. (e.g. the 2011 _Jane Eyre_ ) This latest LW, however, looks a bit fraught -- but I shouldn't judge just by a trailer. I guess I'm saying we have a lot to learn from the 19th century, not the other way around.
author: Lawrence Bottorff

text: So i consider myself a feminist and i agree with everything this trailer stands for, my only problem is why must we always be so PREACHY with our beliefs??? The 90s version showed a really strong, independent and creative Jo without all the dialogue ab “whyyyyyy must a woman...????” Even the 80s Anne of Green Gables/Avonlea with Meagan Follows had strong feminism without all the mouthiness. Anne became a teacher and a writer and just like Jo she shrugged off her best friend but in the end both women get married to somebody😂😂😂😂😂😂😂😂😂😂😂 I think in this day and age women are 100x more independent so the idea that there needs to be a narrative dragging marriage is unnecesaary. You dont even see that type sh*t in films anymore, not when u have female protagonists like Rey or Black Widow, etc. We have been out of the Damsel in Distress ages for yearrrrrssss. So i just feel like the loud message is SERIOUSLY unnecessary. I also dont like the fact that this film seems wayyyyyy too...”modern?” Too relaxed, as if a bunch of besties decided to film a college film project without taking time to learn the accents and behaviors from back in those days. I adore the cast, they were perfect and im tired of timmie getting friend zoned by saoirse (LOLOLOL😂😂😂) but i hope this movie surprises me. I will definitely see it but the accents are super cringey. They all sound like theyre some LA Natives or something😂😂😂😂😂😂😂

text: Triggered: I grew up reading this book and it's a masterpiece, this remake is why I hate modern feminism. This completely side-tracks and subverts the narrative to fit into what we think the author should have meant when she was very clear, in order to fit with what we have now come to make of feminism and it bastardizes a complex, multi-themed, intricate, Bible-lengthed work of litterature and dresses it up as cheap street corner two cents feminism.... Uggggh! It's also porn for celebrity addicts who were dying to see all those actors together -hoorah great actors in a bad movie-, great way to pack the theaters : stars as bait a misleading title when in fact the wisdom of Louisa May Alcott is being butchered.... Laurie was a man of the world in the book, he had mix of delicacy and romanticism in himself, and at the same time was very masculine, especially adult Laurie. Christian Bale was just perfect casting, he has all of it, plus if you read about Bale's life it is almost like he was Laurie. Laurie had a pianist mother and traveled a lot, Bale traveled most of his childhood with his mother's circus and with his father, an ex-pilot. Both Lauire and Bale led an artistic bohemian life at some point. Timothée has romanticism and tenderness, but not enough manhood, he looks like baby all the time. I will watch it in cinema, but I don't have high hopes. Winona&Christian were perfect as Jo&Laurie.

I would take my neice to see this but I want her to hear the original text not modern slang that takes me out of the period! I really hope this will not be the norm now, the dumbing down of classic literature with modern talk and dare I say references! I mean do some thirty something executives think its cute to do this to period pieces now? Or that it will earn them some extra bucks these days if the kids hear relatable slang? I mean you had a great young cast of talents for the Little Women I know from the 90s. Ryder, Dunst, Mathis, Alvarado, Sarandon, Danes. That was the ulimate Little Women cast and this comes close. text: I understand every story is subjected to different interpretations...but as a classic, the interpretations have long come to consensus. It’s a book advocating independence, self reliance and family values. I understand those values are rooted in feminist worldview. But feminist values are so much more intense than the values indicated in the original book. Thus, in my opinion, if anyone has such a different view, and she is capable, it’s best for her to develop her own stories instead ruining our classic. By saying ruining, I mean the future generation may view little women as a feminist book, no, it’s not. It’s written in a time feminism is not such a popular thing.

text: I think it’s a mistake for producers to cast actors who have romantic chemistry to portray Jo and Laurie. It makes way for romanticizing what _should not_ be romanticized; Jo doesn’t have any romantic feelings for Laurie at all, while Laurie doesn’t take “No” for an answer at first. Yet in the comments below, you see people gushing on about Jo/Laurie like they don’t see anything wrong with it.  Seriously, though, you wouldn’t find it nice if your best friend, whom you have no feelings for, proposed to you, and after saying “No,” he still tries to convince you, even though nothing _can_ convince you because you simply don’t have feelings for him. If you don’t have romantic feelings for someone, then you simply don’t. And it just makes the guy a jerk if they continue on after “No.”

text: In 2018 I took a new job as a SPED bus driver.  My route included going on Lowell Road, Concord, near the Newbury Field/Chamberlin Woods area.  Concord is an affluent community.  I noticed a big white tent building with heaters set up in someone's front yard.  I immediately thought that a structure that big and luxurious must be for a film crew.  Though I never saw any film crew, actors or actresses, I still believed the tent was there for their meal breaks.  I now know I was right, as I can see some of the locations in Concord, MA, which are in the film.  And to think that Saoirse "I don't date" Ronan was right there as I drove by. 😢

text: This seems like a really unnecessary adaptation to me and I doubt it'll be better than the 1994 version.    The casting is questionable. The actors are all great in their own right but some of them don't make sense as these characters. It looks like they're going to have Florence Pugh play Amy throughout the entire film but that doesn't really work for the character. She's the youngest at 12 when first introduced. Her relationship with Laurie is supposed to begin as a one sided crush on her part, with him not really noticing her at all until they run into each other in Europe and she's a grown woman. Timothée Chalamet as Laurie doesn't really work either, at least not post time skip. He has a baby face, looks like he's 16 (which will work great for his role as the 15 year old Paul Atreides in Dune!). I also don't think Louis Garrel is old enough, or looks old enough, to play Friedrich Bhaer. He's supposed to be significantly older than Jo.

text: If people want Jo and Laurie to get together then they totally don’t understand Jo at all.  Jo made the right decision when refusing Jo.  She loved him like a sister and a friend.  She knew she couldn’t ever be a society wife and she hated gossip and small talk.  In the end Jo found a man who both loved her and respected her talent as a writer.  The Professor cherished Jo’s unconventional aspirations and encouraged her to write honestly from the heart.  And, when Aunt March died and left Jo her house, the Professor helped her to make her dream of running a boy’s school a reality.  They had a harmonious and fulfilling marriage, ran a successful school and Jo was able to be a wife, mother and writer.  Any and Laurie were also perfect for one another.  Jo and Laurie remained the best of friends.  Perfect ending.
author: Justine McKay

text: SPOILER FOR THOSE WHO HAVEN’T READ THE NOVEL  The line that Jo (Saoirse) says about how she’s “so sick of people saying that love is all a woman is fit for” and that whole monologue wasn’t in the novel. However, those were actually Louisa May Alcott’s words (the author of ‘Little Women’). She said it in response to her fans who kept asking why she finished the novel with Jo ending up with Friedrich instead of Teddy and how Jo choosing to keep her independence would still have been a better ending (I’ve seen this adaptation and it addresses and answers why Alcott had to end it that way.) Greta Gerwig chose to add it in the script as ‘Little Women’ is partly auto-biographical and based Jo off herself.

text: I am a huge fan of Greta Gerwig. From Lady Bird to Frances Ha to Maggie's Plan and more... even her adorable performance in Arthur. Everything she directs and everything she acts in, she turns out golden perfomances. Not only is she beautiful, but she is also smart and multi talented as a director and writer, that would rival many of the top directors and writers of the past and present. I love the 1933 and the 1949 version equally. They both have something special about them and each actress is outstanding in their respective roles. I am very excited to see Greta's vision on this classic masterpiece of novella and theater. Added with one of the greatest and most talented actresses of our time in Saoirse Ronan... Where can it go wrong? It is sure to become a modern classic that equals it's predecessors.

text: Written and directed by Greta Gerwig (who also directed ‘Lady Bird’), this is absolutely the WORST movie I’ve seen in recent years. It unequivocally affirms my worst opinion of Rotten Tomatoes, which positively rates this movie at 95%.  This movie is all-round bad. Its poorly written script fundamentally changes the original story just to inject a ‘faux’ feminist overtone. So is its casting. In trying to distinguish it from previous movie adaptations (and presupposing its audience already knows the story), this movie randomly flips the timeline and sequence of events back-and-forth. Not only does it kill plot cohesion, it fails to give most actors a chance to develop their roles. Purporting to address the issue of feminism of this era (Massachusetts during the Civil War in 1860’s), it blasts marriage as merely an ‘economic proposition’, which is true - except it does so casually in 3 lines of one dialog.   In my view, the 1949 (Elizabeth Taylor) and 1994 (Susan Sarandon) adaptations of ‘Little Women’ are fantastic classics. Why they bother to make such an inferior one in 2019 really beats me. Only guess is : director Greta Gerwig has no clothes !

text: Six remakes since the original nearly a hundred years ago, and this one is different....how?  Jo: Free-spirit, a writer, hot-tempered, non-conformist, longs for love Meg: Lovely, demure, studious, dutiful, honorable Beth: Sweet, peace-maker, quiet, beloved, everyone's heart Amy: Spoiled, jealous, headstrong, reckless, an artist, follows her heart Marmee: Feminist, unofficial head of household, protector of her girls Laurie: Smitten with Jo, confidant with Meg, mourns the loss of Beth, marries Amy  Jo writes stories. Arranges plays for her and her sisters to act out. Is close to her Aunt March. Cuts off her heair and sells it to buy a ticket home for their father who is off fighting. Pursued by Laurie. Meg is happy to be a housewife (much to Jo's chagrin). Beth contracts scarlet fever. Amy causes trouble. Burns Jo's manuscript. Fight ensues. Amy nearly dies. Everyone kisses and makes up. Meg gets married. Jo rebuffs Laurie; sells her manuscript. Becomes a teacher. Amy goes to Paris and is praised for her paintings. Marries Laurie. Jo gets married.  Tell me how anything has changed in 80 years--other than the actresses? Yeah, I think I'll pass.

text: Ho-hum. Movie was passable but unmemorable. Oddly Gerwig spent time at Orchard House talking to the people there about the author, the book, the family--went over Gerwig's head. Bet Orchard House was glad for publicity but cringed by the move. Huge disappointment.   Per the writings and letters of Louisa M Alcott, Marmee was the heart of the home and larger than life--as was Susan Sarandon but not Dern (miscast and also misunderstood Marmee).   The whole movie was very miscast. Watson unmemorable. Flat line delivery by sooooo many.   Chalamet s a brilliant actor and was trying to save the scenes. Ronan was interesting although also miscast and looked too old. As for Florence Pugh as Amy, a complete failure of understanding Alcott's Amy. And as for the "Amy" issue-- should have cast a young and older Amy.   What happened to the script doctors the whole thing needed retooling. A snore on the strange costume choices for the historic period. Durran was obviously going for an award instead of depicting a time period and tone reflective of the book, area, and author and especially the March family.  On an endnote, Alcott had the opportunity of writing letters to the general public to answer everyone's questions about the story and characters so why could they not respect her point of view?    Lastly:  a bow to the set designer and decorators and music. Somebody got it.

text: Deep down, I believe that Jo loves Laurie. She just doesn’t admit it. She pushed it away just bcuz she wanted freedom. At the end she learned how to love and married a man whom she spent time with a lot less. Jo also wrote a letter confessing her love to Laurie even after all these years. She finally accepted the fact that she in fact loves him. She just needed the time to think. Too bad Amy stole him away just in time. I personally think Amy has the worst personality among all sisters, and I was genuinely mad that she was who Laurie chose at the end. Just if Amy wasn’t on the trip back home, and if Laurie would’ve read the letter, I’m certain that he could spent the rest of the life with the woman who he truly loved from the start, but not with a woman who he landed on after Jo. Amy and Laurie together just makes me disgusted, and I dare say, I wouldn’t been so mad if Laurie just ended up with a woman with a better personality. The movie would’ve ended perfectly if Laurie and Jo ended up together. What a bummer.

author: ocwaveoc69

text: In college, I read "Little Women".  In fact, I actually read the book 3 or 4 times before the age of 25.  The message within it's pages was clear, pristine and unsullied.  It was a message that I took to heart and carried with me throughout my adult life.  When I saw this film, all I could see was a political message dressed with a sweet vinaigrette of beautiful costumes, actresses known for their outspoken feminism and writing that went out of its way to oversow the message that Louisa May Alcott so exquisitely embroidered within the pages of her book.   The attempt to capture that delicate and elegant message was anything but delicate and elegant.  The feminist overtones reverberated throughout the film like a Norwegian death metal band trying to play "Queen of the Night Aria" from Mozart's, "The Magic Flute."  It just didn't work.    Stories as sublime as "Little Women" do not require any enhancement.  Otherwise, the power of the story vanishes.  Its like looking at a star in the night sky and only being able to see it by looking just slightly right or left of it.   Anything else, and it vanishes in an instant.  Why use a battering ram when a needle will do?  For whatever it's worth, the film was well acted, well directed and superbly filmed.  Too bad the writer/director lacked the confidence to allow this masterpiece to simply speak for itself.
author: Chris V

text: Amy: “ well I’m not a poet I’m just a women. And as a women there is no way for me to make my own money, not enough to earn a living or to support my family and if I had my own money, which I don’t, the money would belong to my husband the moment we got married, and if we had children they would be his, not mine, they would be his property, so don’t sit there and tell me that marriage isn’t a economic proposition, because it is, maybe not for you but it most certainly is for me!”    Today's man: "Well, I'm not a poet, I'm just a man. And as a man there is no way for me to make my own money, as half of it would go to any wife who chooses to divorce me the moment we were no longer married, and if we had children they would be hers not mine, they would be her property, of which I would need to pay dearly for the privilege of seeing them on occasion, so don't sit there and tell me that marriage isn't an economic proposition, because it is, maybe not for women but it is most certainly for me."    My, how times have changed.

I feel like throughout the whole film Jo just tried to prove she was on the same level as a man, and it cost her the love of her life, being happy and helping keep her family in economic stability. Lets be honest, would Laurie really of fell for Jo in a real life situation? Jo literally had nothing to offer Laurie.  The only likeable thing about Jo I can see through Lauries eyes is that they were both rebellious teens, but when it was time to grow up Jo became unappealing to him even though she rejected him. text: Can I just share something? well because I feel like nobody would resonate with me on this. My professor in college right now has this very traditional way of thinking. One time she said that in this time of age where everybody is getting more freedom we should need to keep an order because that's is how the world could work properly, if everybody gets what they want the world would be in total chaos, which in a way I agree on. But last week she said something that for me is very triggering, she said that she cannot understand what is International Women's Month Celebration is all about. To her isn't women already experiencing and enjoying enough rights so why are they still having this celebration in the first place, why does it seem like they are wanting more? that's her mindset about it. But at that moment I really wanted to answer her but unfortunately I didn't have enough courage. I wanted to tell her that International Women's Month Celebration is all about celebrating being a woman. It is not about women wanting more rights, it is us celebrating the rights that we are currently enjoying which our predecessors did not get to enjoy. And she also added about how men does not have any "Men's Month" and it kinda reminded me of that post about normal people being angry of PWDs having their own parking space. It is like men have been enjoying their rights for as long as the world started and now that women are just starting to enjoy their own rights, people like this come and in a way invalidates them. I wanted to say to her face that "ma'am International Women's Month Celebration is all about celebrating womanhood, femininity and being a woman, it is not us wanting more rights, it is us celebrating the rights that we are currently enjoying which the earlier generation did not able to enjoy. And if you're wondering why there isn't a Men's Month, may I just remind you that men had been in control and enjoying all of their rights since the beginning of time."

text: My favourite book is Louisa May Alcott's "Little Women". It says so much just in one book. A tell of all four girls in their teens, their growth and when they truly become a woman. Meg's growth after her marriage, there are certain life lessons like where her mother advised her to include her husband in raising kids etc, Amy wrote a letter to Joe after she finally found love and that was epic. I love all of them so much. I truly hoped once in my lifetime I would be able to see a good adaptation. This is way too silly for that great book. I really hated the version where Elizabeth Taylor portrayed Amy but this one is surely the worst.
